english:
  title: 'Reflections on High Ridges: Twelve Verses'
  author: Choi Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I come and go on this lonely isle,
    Taking my meals where strangers dwell.
    The women here walk bent and small,
    The people wear poverty like a second skin.
    Their customs strange, yet oddly—
    They observe the forms of respect.

    As sunset falls, the fishy smoke thickens,
    Autumn deepens, the miasma turns warm.
    The peaks rise up, row upon row,
    The tidal flats wind on and on.
    Sails cut through heaven's reflected light,
    Sand dunes mark where the waters once ran.

    I consult the ancient sea charts,
    But the tides—I must ask the boatmen.
    The old trees bow before the wind's edge,
    The startled waves crash against stone, crying out.

    I lodge with monks in shared repose,
    Far removed from the world's clamor.
    I wait with rod and line for the hour,
    And feel the stirring of wandering joy.
    Who will answer my long song?
    I can only sigh, alone and silent.

    Yet know this: the happiness of mist and waves
    Remains the grace of the sovereign's care.
  footnotes:
    - High Ridges (高巒) refers to a small island off the coast west of Buphyeong. The poet likely visited this place to check on his father, Choi Baek-ryun, who had been exiled there.
